Following the question at the end of today's lecture, you might like to
try this...

Suppose we have the data type:

    data List a = Nil | Cons a ( List a )

which is isomorphic to Haskell's [a] type.  Now, on the command line we
can type conventional list expressions, for example:

Prelude> [1,2]
[1,2]
Prelude> [ True, False ]
[True,False]

and so on.  But suppose we instead want to use the List type, as in:

Prelude> Cons 1 ( Cons 2 Nil )
Prelude> Cons True ( Cons False Nil )

In both cases we get an error because List a is not a member of the Show
class.  As an exercise explicitly create an instance of Show (i.e.
instance Show a => Show ( List a ) where ...) which defines show :: List
a -> String such that the above lists are printed in the *same format*
as Haskell's built-in lists.  For example, we want:

Prelude> Cons 1 ( Cons 2 Nil )
[1,2]
Prelude> Cons True ( Cons False Nil )
[True,False]

Note, however, that you won't be able to print lists of characters using
"..." notation (that's a truly built-in capability!).  Hence:

Prelude> Cons ( Cons 'a' Nil ) ( Cons ( Cons 'z' Nil ) Nil )
[['a'],['z']]
Prelude> ( 'a' : [] ) : ( 'z' : [] ) : []
["a","z"]

Finally, note that Int, Bool, Char, etc. are already members of Show so,
for example,

Prelude> show True
"True"
Prelude> show 21
"21"

You may notice (e.g. by doing Prelude> :info Show) that there are two
other member functions in the Show class (showsPrec and showList).  You
do not *have* to define these when you create your instance.




