single answer and 5 from scripts that were identical in all answers. 
 It's up to you how you interpret your final 'score' in these cases - I 
can't judge it on your behalf becase I don't know who really did the work!

I enclose a model answer which is pretty minimal in that it uses 
higher-order functions etc. to reduce the bulk of the code.  Even if you 
didn't solve the problem in exactly the same way you should make sure 
you understand what the model answer is doing.  The original question is 
still available on the Haskell course web page.

Good luck on Friday!  Remember it's only the first HALF of a two-part 
exam.  The second part concerns Prolog which you'll be covering in the 
summer term.

Tony Field.
